qas.question: What does wood retain in its cell walls despite being air-dried?
Air-dried wood keeps up to what percentage of the water in its cell walls?
What kind of dried wood retains a small quantity of water but is considered absolutely dry?

context: In heartwood it occurs only in the first and last forms. Wood that is thoroughly air-dried retains 8–<a1_0>16<a1_0/>% of the <a0_0>water<a0_0/> in the cell walls, and none, or practically none, in the other forms. Even <a2_0>oven-dried<a2_0/> wood retains a small percentage of moisture, but for all except chemical purposes, may be considered absolutely dry.
